  <Fragment slot="headline">Calorie Deficit Guide: How to Use a TDEE Calculator</Fragment>

  <p>A calorie deficit means eating fewer calories than your body uses. That is the basic idea behind fat loss.</p>
  <p>But the hard part is estimating how many calories your body actually burns. That is where a TDEE calculator becomes useful.</p>

  <h2>What TDEE Means</h2>
  <p><strong>TDEE</strong> stands for total daily energy expenditure. It is an estimate of how many calories you burn in a day based on factors like body size, sex, age, and activity level.</p>

  <h2>Why TDEE Matters</h2>
  <p>If you eat above TDEE, you may gain weight. If you eat below TDEE, you create a calorie deficit. If you eat near TDEE, you are closer to maintenance.</p>

  <h2>Calorie Deficit in Simple Terms</h2>
  <p>A deficit is not one fixed number for everyone. A reasonable target depends on your size, activity, adherence, and personal goals.</p>

  <h2>How to Use a TDEE Calculator</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Enter your age, sex, height, and weight.</li>
    <li>Select your activity level honestly.</li>
    <li>Review your estimated maintenance calories.</li>
    <li>Choose a lower target if your goal is fat loss.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>TDEE Is an Estimate, Not a Guarantee</h2>
  <p>Your actual calorie needs may be higher or lower than the estimate. The calculator gives you a starting point that you can adjust based on progress over time.</p>

  <h2>Best Tool to Use</h2>
  <p>Use the <a href="https://mycalcstool.com/en/tdee-calculator"><strong>TDEE Calculator</strong></a> to estimate daily calorie needs and compare maintenance vs lower-calorie targets.</p>

  <h2>Important Note</h2>
  <p>This is general educational information, not medical advice. People with medical conditions, pregnancy, or complex nutrition needs should use professional guidance.</p>

  <h2>Final Takeaway</h2>
  <p>A calorie deficit starts with a realistic estimate of energy use. A TDEE calculator helps you set that starting point quickly and clearly.</p>
